article.headline: Denver 81, New Mexico State 58
article.story: LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) -- In a season where questions are many and answers are few for New Mexico State, perhaps no one has left the Aggies scratching their collective heads more than Yemi Nicholson. In two games against New Mexico State this season, the Denver center has had career nights, scoring 64 points in the two wins. On Saturday night, the 6-10 Nicholson scored 30 points and grabbed 13 rebounds to lead the Pioneers to an 81-58 win over the struggling Aggies in Sun Belt Conference action. "He can take over any game," said Denver point guard Rodney Billups, who had 10 points and six assists. "We're not going to win if we let one person dominate us like that," said New Mexico State's Duane John. NMSU interim head coach Tony Stubblefield was more succinct. "To make a long story short, he's just better," Stubblefield said. "He's a tough matchup." Nicholson, a transfer from Fort Lewis where he was on a music scholarship, scored 16 points in a row early in the second half to help the Pioneers (16-9, 10-3) pull away for the easy win. Many of his baskets finished off fast breaks. Nicholson, who had a career-high 34 points against NMSU two weeks ago in Denver, made all 10 of his free throws Saturday night and was 10-for-15 from the field. Denver was 19-19 from the free throw line. New Mexico State (5-21, 1-12) struggled offensively, shooting 39 percent from the field and 57 percent from the free throw line. It was the Aggies' eighth loss in a row. "We can't win and shoot that percentage," said Stubblefield. NMSU led early in the game, but Denver began to take control midway through the first half when the Pioneers went on an 11-0 run to go up 32-20. After trailing 45-33 at halftime, the Aggies cut the deficit to nine points early in the second half before Nicholson ignited another 11-0 run to put Denver up by 20, 64-44. While Nicholson's scoring outburst helped bury the Aggies, Denver coach Terry Carroll was most proud of his team's defensive effort. "Our defensive intensity was there from the beginning," he said. "We got after them defensively and did a better job of blocking out. We came ready to play." John led NMSU with 17 points, while Josh Jenkins and Jeff Jones added nine points each. Antonio Porch and Andrew Carpenter scored 12 points apiece for Denver, followed by Billups with 10. New Mexico State reserve guard Antwan Alexander missed the contest because of a one-game suspension for breaking a team rule.
